{{notability|date=December 2017}} {{Infobox Organization |name = The Brighton Collaboration |image = Service_Mark_for_the_Brighton_Collaboration_Foundation,_06_September_2012.jpg |image_border = |size = |caption = Service Mark of the Brighton Collaboration Foundation |abbreviation = |vision = Safest, effective vaccines based on rigorous science |formation = {{Start date|2000}} |type = [[non-profit organization|NPO]] |headquarters = [[Basel, Switzerland]] |location = |mission = To enhance the science of vaccine research by providing standardized, validated, and objective methods for continuous monitoring of safety profiles and by assessing benefit-risk ratios. These methods are, in turn, recognized and recommended for use by international regulatory and public health agencies.<ref>[http://www.euvaccine.eu/news-events/news/evi-and-brighton-collaboration-foundation-bcf-sign-memorandum-understanding-mou-mon EVI and Brighton Collaboration Foundation (BCF) sign Memorandum of Understanding (MoU)]</ref>
|region_served = Worldwide |membership = |language = English |leader_title = |leader_name = Jan Bonhoeffer, president |website = [https://brightoncollaboration.org www.brightoncollaboration.org]}}
The '''Brighton Collaboration''' (BC) is a [[non-profit]] global [[vaccine]] safety research network for health care professionals, named after the city in England where the idea was first formulated.
The Brighton Collaboration was launched in 2000 The idea of the collaboration started in 1999, following a presentation by Bob Chen at an international scientific vaccine conference in Brighton, U.K. In his talk, he stressed the need to improve vaccine safety monitoring by developing internationally accepted standards.<ref>[https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/10559533 Chen RT. Vaccine risks: real, perceived and unknown. Vaccine 1999]</ref>
