'''Kwacoco''', sometimes spelled '''kwa-coco''', is a dish consisting in pureed [[Xanthosoma|cocoyam]] (a root crop originated in Central and South America) wrapped and steamed in [[Banana leaf|banana leaves]]. It is consumed by different ethnic groups from [[Cameroon]], specially the [[Kwe people]], for whom the traditional meal usually consists in kwacoco served with [[banga (soup)|banga]], which is a soup made from a base of palm nut pulp, and smoked fish.<ref>{{Citation| last=Ngoran | first=Suinyuy Derrick  | year=2008| title= Unpinning Village Development in Cameroon: The Case of Bakingili Village. | publisher=GRIN Verlag | publication-place= | page=| url=http://www.grin.com/en/e-book/268072/unpinning-village-development-in-cameroon-the-case-of-bakingili-village| accessdate= 16 October 2016}}</ref> It is sometimes referred to as ''kwacoco bible'' when the cocoyam is mixed with other ingredients such as spinach, smoked fish, red oil and spices,<ref>{{Citation| last=Forsac-Tata | first=D. | year=2016| title= Community-based tourism in the South West region of Cameroon: Opportunities and challenges for women. | journal= IOSR Journal of Humanities and Social Science|publisher= | publication-place= | page=114| url=https://www.academia.edu/download/45614830/IOSR_Published_Article.pdf| accessdate= 16 October 2016}}</ref> and it can also be served along with many other stews and soups.

The combination of kwacoco and banga is a staple food for rural communities in Cameroon, who rely on the [[fat]]s and [[carbohydrate]]s provided by these foods to subsist.<ref>{{Citation| last=Mungah Shalo Tchombe | first=Therese | year=2016| title= Psychological Undertones of Family Poverty in Rural Communities in Cameroon: Resilience and Coping Strategies. | journal= South African Journal of Psychology|volume=42| issue=2 | publication-place= | pages=232–242| url=http://sap.sagepub.com/content/42/2/232.short| accessdate= 16 October 2016}}</ref> During the [[2007–08 world food price crisis|world food crisis of 2008]], local farmers were encouraged to produce more cocoyam, and urban consumers were told to promote its consumption over imported food.<ref>{{Citation| last1=De Lancey | first1=Mark Dike | last2=Mbuh | first2=Rebecca | year=2010 | last3=De Lancey | first3=Mark W.| title= Historical Dictionary of the Republic of Cameroon. | publisher= Scarecrow Press | page=103| url=https://books.google.fr/books?id=4l9lSZ9d46cC| accessdate= 16 October 2016}}</ref>

